{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, the term **tasawwur** appears in the poem \"Himalaya\" (Chapter 25). There, it is personified and directly apostrophized (\"ae tasawwur\") as an imaginative or visualizing faculty capable of conjuring visions of the past.[^1] The translator renders it as **Fantasy** in this context:\n\n> O, show me, **Fantasy**, that dawn and dusk once more![^2]  \n> O, wheel of time, turn back to days that came before!\n\nThis invocation follows the poet's request to the Himalaya to recount humanity's primordial simplicity, positioning *tasawwur* as the creative power to mentally reconstruct or visualize lost eras of innocence.[^3]\n\nNo other uses of *tasawwur* appear in the *Bang-E-Dara* portions of the corpus.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 25 \"Himalaya\" (transliteration), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/transliteration/#p-417cdf).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 25 \"Himalaya\" (translation), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-417cdf).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 25 \"Himalaya\" (translation), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-0675a0).",
